raw._content: PHOTO BY: VERNON PUGH.(February 21, 1997). . . .The NavyÕs newest strike-fighter aircraft, the F/A-18E ÒSuper HornetÓ successfully completed its first in-flight tests with ordnance.  The weapons package consisted of two 2000lbs bombs, two AGM 88 Anti-Radiation missiles, and two AIM 9 Heat Seeking Sidewider missiles.  With 14,000lbs of ordnance, ÒSuper HornetÓ took to the air weighing 62,000,400lbs with fuel.  The aircraft was piloted by form Marine aviator Mr. Jim Sandberg, a member of the Integrated Test Team (ITT), located at Naval Air Station Patuxent River, Maryland.  The Super Hornet replaces the A-6 ÒIntruderÓ which will end active naval service on 28 February 1997, and is the future programmed replacement for the F-14 ÒTomcatÓ.  An evolutionary upgrade to the combat proven ÒCÓ & ÒDÓ series, Super Hornet will conduct both air-to-air and air-to-ground combat missions.  Improvements include increases in fuel capacity, engine power, mission radius (40%), weapons stations, aircraft surface area (25%), and itÕs ability to remain on station during typical combat air patrol scenarios.  The ÒSuper HornetÓ development program continues to be Òon-timeÓ and under budget.  U.S. Navy Photo Courtesy McDonnell Douglas Corp. (Released)
